claim:slides-as-primary-artefact  a fair2r:Claim ;
    rdfs:label "Slide decks (slides/*.md) join the manuscript, the PROV-O graph, and the logbook as the fourth primary artefact under the consistency invariant. A claim graduates to a slide only after it has graduated to the paper text; a slide that contradicts the paper is a defect surfaced by the FAIR Aligner."@en ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo agent:human-author ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy  act:rev-add-slide-decks ;
    fair2r:verificationState verif:human-confirmed ;
    dcterms:created "2026-05-06"^^xsd:date .

hc:slide-decks               a fair2r:HumanContribution ;
    rdfs:label "Researcher request: two slide decks (5-minute pitch + 25+5 conference) on the DLR design system, treated as primary artefacts, included in CI; create a fitting presentation agent"@en ;
    fair2r:contributedBy agent:human-author ;
    fair2r:contributionType "structural-decision" ;
    fair2r:contributionLeverage "high" ;
    rdfs:comment "Researcher proposed: 'every paper needs a slide deck. I want you to design 2 slide decks. A 5 minute pitch deck and a 25+5 conference deck for the paper. can you generate it using the DLR DESIGN system. both should be treated as primary artifacts. included in ci. create a fitting presentation agent'. Two decks added under slides/, vendored marp-dlr theme under slides/static/dlr/, slides/Makefile + .github/workflows/build-slides.yml for CI, agents/presentation.md as the slide-deck custodian, CLAUDE.md and doc/methodology.md updated to make slides the fourth primary artefact."@en ;
    dcterms:created "2026-05-06"^^xsd:date ;
    prov:influenced ent:slidedeck-pitch ,
                    ent:slidedeck-conference ,
                    ent:prompt-presentation ,
                    ent:workflow-build-slides ,
                    claim:slides-as-primary-artefact .

hc:obs-coding-structure        a fair2r:MetaContribution ;
    rdfs:label "Coding with LLMs: structure becomes more important; visions, feature sets, dependencies are the human's load (the coding-counterpart of the writing partition); domain vocabulary fluency is a collaboration multiplier"@en ;
    fair2r:contributedBy agent:human-author ;
    fair2r:contributionType "observation" ;
    fair2r:contributionLeverage "high" ;
    fair2r:promotedToPaper "pending" ;
    rdfs:comment "Researcher observed during the slide-decks session: 'In coding with LLMs somehow structure becomes more important, like guiding and shaping a river of code --- it's more about visions, feature sets, dependencies.' Extended in the next message: 'addition to the river thought, as a dev / cs engineer i have the vocabulary to effectively work with the llm by referring to things more specifically producing a more general cohesiveness'. The model identified this as the coding-counterpart of the writing partition (same partition, same coupling rule, same diagnostic). The vocabulary-fluency extension adds a second layer to the equity discussion in §sustainability: it is not just access to frontier models that is asymmetric, it is access to the formal vocabulary that makes the cooperation effective. Researchers from disciplines with rich shared formal vocabularies (CS, mathematics, physics, well-formalised parts of biology) start with an advantage that does not transfer to disciplines whose vocabularies are still being built. The eight integrated practices of F(AI)^2R are themselves a vocabulary for cooperative writing; the act of naming them gives a future researcher a set of API terms to reach for. The paper's contribution, on this reading, is partly the practices and partly the vocabulary that lets a researcher operate them precisely."@en ;
    dcterms:created "2026-05-06"^^xsd:date .

ent:script-build-slides        a prov:Entity ;
    rdfs:label "scripts/build_slides.py (DLR-theme asset-inlining preprocessor + Marp wrapper)"@en ;
    dcterms:source <scripts/build_slides.py> .

act:rev-fix-slide-rendering    a prov:Activity ;
    rdfs:label "Fix slide rendering: port marp-dlr's run-marp.mjs asset-inlining preprocessor to Python so the DLR background plates and logos actually load in headless Chromium"@en ;
    prov:startedAtTime "2026-05-06T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    prov:endedAtTime   "2026-05-06T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    prov:wasAssociatedWith agent:claude-opus-4-7 ;
    prov:wasAssociatedWith agent:human-author ;
    prov:generated ent:script-build-slides .

ent:script-build-slides        prov:wasGeneratedBy act:rev-fix-slide-rendering .

hc:fix-slide-rendering         a fair2r:HumanContribution ;
    rdfs:label "Researcher report: slides don't adhere to the DLR design system; pages reverted to old look"@en ;
    fair2r:contributedBy agent:human-author ;
    fair2r:contributionType "corrective-intervention" ;
    fair2r:contributionLeverage "high" ;
    rdfs:comment "Researcher reported two issues after PR #16: (a) the rendered slides did not actually look DLR-themed; (b) the deployed Pages site appeared to revert to an older version. Diagnosis: (a) The naïve 'marp --theme path/to/dlr.css' invocation we used does not pre-process the theme CSS the way the canonical marp-dlr framework does. The framework's run-marp.mjs inlines every url('./assets/...') reference as a base64 data URI before passing the CSS to Marp; without that step, the title and section-divider background plates and the DLR logos never load in headless Chromium and the deck rendering looks unstyled. We ported the preprocessor to Python (scripts/build_slides.py) and the slide Makefile and CI now use it. (b) Likely a CDN cache: the slide-only PR did not match the path filter on pages.yml, so the site did not re-deploy. Touched site/index.md in this commit so the merge triggers a fresh Pages deploy, which busts the cache. The cache-busting scheme on asset URLs (style.css?v=hash) is unchanged."@en ;
    dcterms:created "2026-05-06"^^xsd:date ;
    prov:influenced ent:script-build-slides ,
                    ent:slidedeck-pitch ,
                    ent:slidedeck-conference ,
                    ent:workflow-build-slides .

hc:obs-latency-as-feature      a fair2r:MetaContribution ;
    rdfs:label "Latency between prompt and response is a cognitive feature, not a bug; it allows formulation work and short context switches (e.g. checking on a coding agent in another window)"@en ;
    fair2r:contributedBy agent:human-author ;
    fair2r:contributionType "observation" ;
    fair2r:contributionLeverage "high" ;
    fair2r:promotedToPaper "pending" ;
    rdfs:comment "Two-part observation: (a) near-instantaneous LLM responses would degrade user-as-co-author into user-as-consumer because formulation pauses (the abstracting work) would compress out of existence; (b) the wait window is productive parallel-tracking time, amortising context-switch cost across slow loops the human author is already running (coding agent, CI, colleague Slack). Candidate sentence for the coupling-rule paragraph in authors-note.tex; possible candidate ninth integrated practice (the supervisory-glance pattern). Marked pending for researcher endorsement."@en ;
    dcterms:created "2026-05-06"^^xsd:date .

hc:obs-accelerator-or-blender  a fair2r:MetaContribution ;
    rdfs:label "Accelerator or cultural blender? --- the cognition question"@en ;
    fair2r:contributedBy agent:human-author ;
    fair2r:contributionType "observation" ;
    fair2r:contributionLeverage "high" ;
    fair2r:promotedToPaper "yes" ;
    rdfs:comment "Graduated to paper text 2026-05-06 as the second-order finding in paper/sections/authors-note.tex, *What surprised me about the cooperation*. The coupling-rule formulation (accelerator on the prose-craft side; cultural blender if it crosses into the abstracting layer) supplies the reason the human-deciding / model-drafting partition matters."@en ;
    dcterms:created "2026-05-06"^^xsd:date .

claim:contribution-tracking-rule  a fair2r:Claim ;
    rdfs:label "Every material contribution to the manuscript or its scaffolding is logged in doc/user-contributions.md (mirrored as fair2r:HumanContribution / AIContribution / MetaContribution in the graph), so that the question 'what did the human / AI actually do here?' has a structured, queryable answer."@en ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo agent:human-author ;
    fair2r:verificationState verif:human-confirmed ;
    dcterms:created "2026-05-06"^^xsd:date .

